A **bagel** ([Yiddish](/wiki/Yiddish_language "Yiddish language"): בײגל,
[romanized](/wiki/Romanization_of_Yiddish "Romanization of Yiddish"): _beygl_
; [Polish](/wiki/Polish_language "Polish language"): _bajgiel_ ; also spelled
**beigel** )[1] is a [bread roll](/wiki/Bread_roll "Bread roll") originating
in the [Jewish communities](/wiki/History_of_Jews_in_Poland "History of Jews
in Poland") of [Poland](/wiki/Poland "Poland").[2] It is traditionally shaped
by hand into a roughly hand-sized ring from [yeasted](/wiki/Yeast "Yeast")
[wheat](/wiki/Wheat "Wheat") dough that is first
[boiled](/wiki/Boiling_in_cooking "Boiling in cooking") for a short time in
water and then [baked](/wiki/Baking "Baking"). The result is a dense, chewy,
doughy interior with a browned and sometimes crisp exterior.

Bagels are often topped with seeds baked on the outer crust—traditional
choices include [poppy](/wiki/Poppy "Poppy") and [sesame](/wiki/Sesame
"Sesame") seeds—or with [salt](/wiki/Salt "Salt") grains. Different dough
types include whole-grain and rye.[3][4] The basic roll-with-a-hole design,
hundreds of years old, allows even cooking and baking of the dough; it also
allows groups of bagels to be gathered on a string or dowel for handling,
transportation, and retail display.[5][6]

The earliest known mention of a boiled-then-baked ring-shaped bread can be
found in a 13th-century Syrian cookbook, where they are referred to as
_[ka'ak](/wiki/Ka%27ak "Ka'ak")_.[7] Bagel-like bread known as
[obwarzanek](/wiki/Obwarzanek_krakowski "Obwarzanek krakowski") was common
earlier in Poland as seen in royal family accounts from 1394.[8] Bagels have
been widely associated with [Ashkenazi Jews](/wiki/Ashkenazi_Jews "Ashkenazi
Jews") since the 17th century; they were first mentioned in 1610 in Jewish
community ordinances in [Kraków](/wiki/Krak%C3%B3w "Kraków"), Poland.[2]

Bagels are now a popular bread product in North America and Poland, especially
in cities with a large [Jewish](/wiki/Jews "Jews") population.[2] Bagels are
also sold (fresh or frozen, often in many flavors) in supermarkets.

## History

Linguist [Leo Rosten](/wiki/Leo_Rosten "Leo Rosten") wrote in _The Joys of
Yiddish_ about the first known mention of the Polish word _bajgiel_ derived
from the Yiddish word _bagel_ in the "Community Regulations" of the city of
[Kraków](/wiki/Krak%C3%B3w "Kraków") in 1610, which stated that the food was
given as a gift to women in childbirth.[9] There is some evidence that the
bagel may have been made in Germany before being made in Poland.[2][10]

In the 16th and first half of the 17th centuries, the _bajgiel_ became a
staple of [Polish cuisine](/wiki/Polish_cuisine "Polish cuisine").[11] Its
name derives from the Yiddish word _beygal_ from the German dialect word
_beugel_ , meaning 'ring' or 'bracelet'.[12]

Variants of the word _beugal_ are used in [Yiddish](/wiki/Yiddish "Yiddish")
and in [Austrian German](/wiki/Austrian_German "Austrian German") to refer to
a similar form of sweet-filled pastry; _Mohnbeugel_ , a pastry filled with
[poppy seeds](/wiki/Poppy_seed "Poppy seed"), and _Nussbeugel_ , a pastry
filled with ground nuts. The term is also used in southern German dialects,
where _beuge_ refers to a pile, e.g., _holzbeuge_ ('woodpile'). According to
the Merriam-Webster dictionary, _bagel_ derives from the transliteration of
the Yiddish _beygl_ , which came from the [Middle High
German](/wiki/Middle_High_German "Middle High German") _böugel_ or 'ring',
which itself came from _bouc_ ('ring') in [Old High
German](/wiki/Old_High_German "Old High German"), similar to the [Old
English](/wiki/Old_English "Old English") _bēag_ ('ring') and _būgan_ ('to
bend, bow').[13] Similarly, another [etymology](/wiki/Etymology "Etymology")
in the Webster's New World College Dictionary says that the Middle High German
form was derived from the [Austrian German](/wiki/Austrian_German "Austrian
German") _beugel_ , a kind of [croissant](/wiki/Croissant "Croissant"), and
was similar to the German _bügel_ , a stirrup or ring.[14]

In the [Brick Lane](/wiki/Brick_Lane "Brick Lane") district and surrounding
area of [London](/wiki/London "London"), England, bagels (locally spelled
"beigels") have been sold since the middle of the 19th century. They were
often displayed in the windows of bakeries on vertical wooden dowels, up to a
metre in length, on racks.[ _[citation needed](/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed
"Wikipedia:Citation needed")_ ]

Bagels with [cream cheese](/wiki/Cream_cheese "Cream cheese") and [lox (cured
salmon)](/wiki/Lox "Lox") are considered a traditional part of American
[Jewish cuisine](/wiki/Jewish_cuisine "Jewish cuisine") (colloquially known as
"lox and a _schmear_ ").

Bagels were brought to the [United States](/wiki/United_States "United
States") by immigrant Polish Jews, with a thriving business developing in [New
York City](/wiki/New_York_City "New York City") that was controlled for
decades by [Bagel Bakers Local 338](/wiki/Bagel_Bakers_Local_338 "Bagel Bakers
Local 338"). They had contracts with nearly all bagel bakeries in and around
the city for its workers, who prepared all their bagels by hand.[15]

The bagel came into more general use throughout [North
America](/wiki/North_America "North America") in the last quarter of the 20th
century with automation. [Daniel Thompson](/wiki/Daniel_Thompson_\(inventor\)
"Daniel Thompson \(inventor\)") started work on the first commercially viable
[bagel machine](/wiki/Bagel_machine "Bagel machine") in 1958; bagel baker
[Harry Lender](/wiki/Lender%27s_Bagels "Lender's Bagels"), his son, [Murray
Lender](/wiki/Murray_Lender "Murray Lender"), and [Florence
Sender](/wiki/Florence_Sender "Florence Sender") leased this technology and
pioneered automated production and distribution of frozen bagels in the
1960s.[16][17][18] Murray also invented pre-slicing the bagel.[19]

Around 1900, the "bagel brunch" became popular in New York City.[20] The bagel
brunch consists of a bagel topped with [lox](/wiki/Lox "Lox"), cream cheese,
[capers](/wiki/Caper "Caper"), tomato, and red onion.[20] This and similar
combinations of toppings have remained associated with bagels into the 21st
century in the United States.[21][22][23]

In [Japan](/wiki/Japan "Japan"), the first kosher bagels were brought by
[BagelK](/w/index.php?title=BagelK&action=edit&redlink=1 "BagelK \(page does
not exist\)")
[[ja](https://ja.wikipedia.org/wiki/%E3%83%99%E3%83%BC%E3%82%B0%E3%83%ABK
"ja:ベーグルK")] from New York in 1989. BagelK created green tea, chocolate,
maple-nut, and banana-nut flavors for the market in Japan. Some Japanese
bagels, such as those sold by [BAGEL &
BAGEL](/w/index.php?title=BAGEL_%26_BAGEL&action=edit&redlink=1 "BAGEL & BAGEL
\(page does not exist\)") [[ja](https://ja.wikipedia.org/wiki/BAGEL_%26_BAGEL
"ja:BAGEL & BAGEL")], are soft and sweet; others, such as [Einstein Bro.
bagels](/wiki/Einstein_Bros._Bagels "Einstein Bros. Bagels") sold by
[Costco](/wiki/Costco "Costco") in Japan, are the same as in the U.S.[
_[citation needed](/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed "Wikipedia:Citation
needed")_ ]

### Size change over time

Bagels in the U.S. have increased in size over time. Starting at around 2
ounces (57 g),[24] by 1915, the average bagel weighed 3 ounces (85 g);[15] the
size began to increase further in the 1960s.[24] By 2003, the average bagel
sold on a Manhattan coffee cart weighed around 6 ounces (170 g).[15]

At its most basic, traditional bagel dough contains wheat flour (without
[germ](/wiki/Cereal_germ "Cereal germ") or [bran](/wiki/Bran "Bran")), salt,
water, and [yeast](/wiki/Baker%27s_yeast "Baker's yeast")
[leavening](/wiki/Leavening_agent "Leavening agent"). [Bread
flour](/wiki/Wheat_flour#United_States "Wheat flour") or other high
[gluten](/wiki/Gluten "Gluten") flours are preferred to create the firm, dense
but spongy bagel shape and chewy texture.[3] With a [dough
hydration](/wiki/Baker_percentage#Dough_hydration "Baker percentage") of
around 50-57%, bagel dough is among the stiffest bread doughs.[25] Most bagel
recipes call for the addition of a sweetener to the dough, often [barley
malt](/wiki/Barley_malt "Barley malt") (syrup or crystals), honey, [high
fructose corn syrup](/wiki/High_fructose_corn_syrup "High fructose corn
syrup"), or [sugar](/wiki/Sugar "Sugar"), with or without eggs, milk or
butter.[3] Leavening can be accomplished using a [sourdough](/wiki/Sourdough
"Sourdough") technique or a commercially produced yeast.

Bagels are traditionally made by:

  * mixing and kneading the ingredients to form the dough
  * shaping the dough into the traditional bagel shape, round with a hole in the middle, from a long thin piece of dough
  * [proofing](/wiki/Proofing_\(baking_technique\) "Proofing \(baking technique\)") the bagels for at least 12 hours at low temperature (40–50 °F (4–10 °C))
  * boiling each bagel in water for 60–90 seconds that may contain additives such as [lye](/wiki/Lye "Lye"), [baking soda](/wiki/Baking_soda "Baking soda"), [barley malt syrup](/wiki/Barley_malt_syrup "Barley malt syrup"), or [honey](/wiki/Honey "Honey")
  * baking at a temperature between 347–599 °F (175–315 °C)

This production method gives bagels their distinctive taste, chewy texture,
and shiny appearance.

In recent years, a variant has emerged, producing what is sometimes called the
steam bagel. To make a steam bagel, the boiling is skipped, and the bagels are
instead baked in an oven equipped with a steam injection system.[26] In
commercial bagel production, the steam bagel process requires less labor,
since bagels need only be directly handled once, at the shaping stage.
Thereafter, the bagels need never be removed from their pans as they are
refrigerated and then steam-baked. The steam bagel results in a fluffier,
softer, less chewy product more akin to a [finger roll](/wiki/Bread_roll
"Bread roll") that happens to be shaped like a bagel. The dough used is
intentionally more [alkaline](/wiki/Base_\(chemistry\) "Base \(chemistry\)")
to aid browning, because the steam injection process uses neutral water steam
instead of an alkaline solution bath.[ _[citation
needed](/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed "Wikipedia:Citation needed")_ ]

Bagels can be frozen for up to six months.[27]

## Quality

According to a 2012 _[Consumer Reports](/wiki/Consumer_Reports "Consumer
Reports")_ article, the ideal bagel should have a slightly crispy crust, a
distinct "pull" when a piece is separated from the whole by biting or
pinching, a chewy inside, and the flavor of bread freshly baked. The taste may
be complemented by additions cooked on the bagel, such as onion, garlic,
sesame seeds, or poppy seeds. The appeal of a bagel may change upon being
toasted. Toasting can have the effect of bringing or removing desirable
chewiness, softening the crust, and moderating off-flavors.[28]

A typical[ _[clarification needed](/wiki/Wikipedia:Please_clarify
"Wikipedia:Please clarify")_ ] bagel has 260–350 calories, 1.0–4.5 grams of
fat, 330–660 milligrams of sodium, and 2–5 grams of fiber. Gluten-free bagels
have much more fat, often 9 grams, because of ingredients in the dough to
supplant the wheat flour of the original.[28]

## Varieties

### New York style

Main article: [New York style bagel](/wiki/New_York_style_bagel "New York
style bagel")

The New York bagel contains malt, is cold-fermented for several days to
develop the flavors and enhance the crust, and is boiled in salted water
before baking in a standard oven.[29] The resulting bagel has a fluffy
interior and a chewy crust. According to CNN, Brooklynites believe New York
bagels are the best due to [the quality of the local
water](/wiki/New_York_City_water_supply_system "New York City water supply
system").[30] According to Brooklyn Water Bagels CEO Steven Fassberg, the
characteristics of a New York bagel are the result of the recipe formula and
preparation method.[30]

### Montreal style

Main article: [Montreal-style bagel](/wiki/Montreal-style_bagel "Montreal-
style bagel")

[![](//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/8c/Bagels-Montreal-
REAL.jpg/240px-Bagels-Montreal-REAL.jpg)](/wiki/File:Bagels-Montreal-REAL.jpg)

[](/wiki/File:Bagels-Montreal-REAL.jpg "Enlarge")

Three [Montreal-style bagels](/wiki/Montreal-style_bagel "Montreal-style
bagel"): one [poppy](/wiki/Poppy_seed "Poppy seed") and two
[sesame](/wiki/Sesame_seed "Sesame seed") bagels

Different from the New York style, the Montreal-style bagel contains
[malt](/wiki/Malt "Malt") and sugar with no salt; it is boiled in honey-
sweetened water before baking in a wood-fired oven. It is predominantly of the
[sesame](/wiki/Sesame "Sesame") "white" seeds variety (bagels in
[Toronto](/wiki/Toronto,_Ontario "Toronto, Ontario") are similar to those made
in New York in that they are less sweet, generally are coated with poppy seeds
and are baked in a standard oven).[ _[citation
needed](/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed "Wikipedia:Citation needed")_ ]

### St. Louis style

The [St. Louis](/wiki/St._Louis "St. Louis") style bagel refers not to
composition, but to a particular method of slicing the bagel.[31] The St.
Louis style bagels are sliced vertically multiple times, instead of the
traditional single horizontal slice.[31] The slices range from 3 to 6 mm (0.12
to 0.24 in) thick.[32] This style of bagel was popularized by the [St. Louis
Bread Company](/wiki/St._Louis_Bread_Company "St. Louis Bread Company"), now
known as [Panera Bread](/wiki/Panera_Bread "Panera Bread").[31] Generally, the
bagels are sliced into eight pieces using a [bread slicer](/wiki/Bread_slicer
"Bread slicer"), which produces characteristically precise cuts (the bagel is
not torn or crushed while slicing).[32] This particular method of preparation
increases the surface area available for [spreads](/wiki/Spread_\(food\)
"Spread \(food\)") (e.g., [cream cheese](/wiki/Cream_cheese "Cream cheese"),
[butter](/wiki/Butter "Butter")).[31] However, it decreases the portability of
the bagel and prevents formation of [sandwiches](/wiki/Sandwich
"Sandwich").[33]

### Other bagel styles

Other bagel styles can be found elsewhere; [Chicago](/wiki/Chicago
"Chicago")-style bagels are baked with steam. American chef [John
Mitzewich](/wiki/John_Mitzewich "John Mitzewich") has a recipe for what he
calls San Francisco-style bagels which yields bagels flatter than New York-
style bagels, characterized by a rough-textured crust. The traditional
[London](/wiki/London "London") bagel (or beigel as it is spelled) is chewier
and has a denser texture.

In Austria, _beigl_ (often also spelled _beigerl_ or _beugerl_ in its
diminutive form) are a traditional [Lenten](/wiki/Lent "Lent") food. The rings
are made from a yeasted dough, rolled out very thin and briefly boiled in
salted water before topped with salt and caraway seeds and then baked.
Depending on the region, they are sometimes baked to a very hard consistency,
making them relatively brittle. Connected with it is the tradition of
_Beiglreißen_ (lit. 'ripping/tearing the _beigl_ ') at Easter where two people
pull on opposite ends of a _beigl_ until it breaks into two pieces. Tearing
off the larger piece is meant to bring good luck.[34] In [Vienna](/wiki/Vienna
"Vienna"), Eastern [Lower Austria](/wiki/Lower_Austria "Lower Austria") and
[Burgenland](/wiki/Burgenland "Burgenland"), _beugerl_ has taken on the
meaning of certain types of [kipferl](/wiki/Kipferl "Kipferl").[35]

## Non-traditional doughs and types

While normally and traditionally made of [yeasted](/wiki/Yeast "Yeast")
[wheat](/wiki/Wheat "Wheat"), in the late 20th century variations on the bagel
flourished. Non-traditional versions that change the dough recipe include
[pumpernickel](/wiki/Pumpernickel "Pumpernickel"), [rye](/wiki/Rye "Rye"),
[sourdough](/wiki/Sourdough "Sourdough"), [bran](/wiki/Bran "Bran"), [whole
wheat](/wiki/Whole_wheat "Whole wheat"), and
[multigrain](/wiki/Multigrain_bread "Multigrain bread"). Other variations
change the flavor of the dough, often using [blueberry](/wiki/Blueberry
"Blueberry"), [salt](/wiki/Salt "Salt"), [onion](/wiki/Onion "Onion"),
[garlic](/wiki/Garlic "Garlic"), [egg](/wiki/Egg_\(food\) "Egg \(food\)"),
[cinnamon](/wiki/Cinnamon "Cinnamon"), [raisin](/wiki/Raisin "Raisin"),
[chocolate chip](/wiki/Chocolate_chip "Chocolate chip"), [cheese](/wiki/Cheese
"Cheese"), or some combination of the above. Green bagels are sometimes
created for [St. Patrick's Day](/wiki/St._Patrick%27s_Day "St. Patrick's
Day").[36]

A flat bagel, known as a 'flagel', can be found in a few locations in and
around New York City, [Long Island](/wiki/Long_Island "Long Island"), and
Toronto. According to a review attributed to New York's _[Village
Voice](/wiki/Village_Voice "Village Voice")_ food critic Robert Seitsema, the
flagel was first created by [Brooklyn's](/wiki/Brooklyn "Brooklyn") 'Tasty
Bagels' [deli](/wiki/Delicatessen "Delicatessen") in the early 1990s.[37]

## Similar breads

[![](//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/5d/Bublik_in_Kiev_with_Sesame.JPG/220px-
Bublik_in_Kiev_with_Sesame.JPG)](/wiki/File:Bublik_in_Kiev_with_Sesame.JPG)

[](/wiki/File:Bublik_in_Kiev_with_Sesame.JPG "Enlarge")

Ukrainian _bublik_

Many cultures developed similar breads and preparations, such as
_[bubliki](/wiki/Bublik "Bublik")_ in [Russia](/wiki/Russia "Russia"),
[Ukraine](/wiki/Ukraine "Ukraine") and [Belarus](/wiki/Belarus "Belarus"), and
_obwarzanek_ (in particular _[obwarzanek krakowski](/wiki/Obwarzanek_krakowski
"Obwarzanek krakowski")_ ) in Poland. Somewhat similar in appearance to
bagels, these breads are usually topped with sesame and poppy seeds. The
ingredients in these breads and bagels somewhat differ, as these breads are
made with a different dough using [butter](/wiki/Butter "Butter").[41] and
sometimes also with milk.[42]

In Italy, _[taralli](/wiki/Taralli "Taralli")_ and
_[friselle](/w/index.php?title=Friselle&action=edit&redlink=1 "Friselle \(page
does not exist\)") [[it](https://it.wikipedia.org/wiki/Frisella
"it:Frisella")]_ are breads similar to bagels.

In [Turkey](/wiki/Turkey "Turkey"), a salty and fattier form is called _açma_.
The ring-shaped [simit](/wiki/Simit "Simit") is sometimes marketed today as a
Turkish bagel. Archival sources show that the _simit_ has been produced in
Istanbul since 1525.[43] Based on Üsküdar court records (Şer’iyye Sicili)
dated 1593,[44] the weight and price of simit was standardized for the first
time. Noted 17th-century traveler [Evliya Çelebi](/wiki/Evliya_%C3%87elebi
"Evliya Çelebi") wrote that there were 70 simit bakeries in Istanbul during
the 1630s.[45]

Jean Brindesi's early 19th-century oil paintings about Istanbul daily life
show simit sellers on the streets.[46] [Warwick Goble](/wiki/Warwick_Goble
"Warwick Goble") made an illustration of the simit sellers of Istanbul in
1906.[47] Simit is very similar to the twisted sesame-sprinkled bagels
pictured being sold in early 20th century Poland. _Simit_ are also sold on the
street in baskets or carts, as bagels were then.[ _[citation
needed](/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed "Wikipedia:Citation needed")_ ]

The [Uyghurs](/wiki/Uyghur_people "Uyghur people") of
[Xinjiang](/wiki/Xinjiang "Xinjiang"), [China](/wiki/China "China") enjoy
_girdeh nan_ (from [Persian](/wiki/Persian_language "Persian language"),
meaning round bread), a type of [nan](/wiki/Naan "Naan"), the local bread.[48]

Another bagel-like type of bread is the traditional German _Dortmunder
Salzkuchen_ from the 19th century.[49]

Ka'ak al-Quds (better known in English as the Jerusalem bagel) is an oblong
ring bread, usually topped with sesame seeds, with its origins in Jerusalem.
Unlike the bagel, it is not boiled prior to baking.[50]

## Cultural references

"Bagel" is also a [Yeshivish](/wiki/Yeshivish "Yeshivish") term for sleeping
12 hours straight—e.g., "I slept a bagel last night." There are various
opinions as to the origins of this term. It may be a reference to the fact
that bagel dough has to "rest" for at least 12 hours between mixing and
baking[2]: 4–5 or simply to the fact that the hour hand on a clock traces a
bagel shape over the course of 12 hours.[ _[citation
needed](/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed "Wikipedia:Citation needed")_ ]

In tennis, a "[bagel](/wiki/Bagel_\(tennis\) "Bagel \(tennis\)")" refers to a
player winning a set 6–0; winning a match 6–0, 6–0, 6–0 is called a "triple
bagel".[51]

" _[Bublichki](/wiki/Bublichki_\(song\) "Bublichki \(song\)")_ " or "
_Bagelach_ " is a title of a famous Russian and Yiddish song written in
[Odessa](/wiki/Odessa "Odessa") in the 1920s. [The Barry
Sisters](/wiki/The_Barry_Sisters "The Barry Sisters") together with the [Ziggy
Elman Orchestra](/wiki/Ziggy_Elman "Ziggy Elman") made it popular in the US in
1939. Today it belongs to the repertoire of [klezmer](/wiki/Klezmer
"Klezmer"), [jazz](/wiki/Jazz "Jazz") and pop musicians.[ _[citation
needed](/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed "Wikipedia:Citation needed")_ ]

In [Quizbowl](/wiki/Quiz_bowl "Quiz bowl"), a "bagel" refers to failing to
correctly answer any part of a multi-part bonus question (i.e. "We bageled
that bonus on the [Franco-Mongol alliance](/wiki/Franco-Mongol_alliance
"Franco-Mongol alliance") in the first finals match."). This is because a
bagel looks like the number zero, which is the points gained by incorrectly
answering all of the questions.[52]

In the [United States](/wiki/United_States "United States"), February 9 is
often celebrated as National Bagel Day,[53] in which people celebrate the rich
history of getting together and eating bagels.[ _[citation
needed](/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed "Wikipedia:Citation needed")_ ]

The term "bageling" refers to when a Jew uses a Jewish word or phrase in a
conversation, or in the vicinity of a stranger who is also clearly Jewish, in
order to inform them that they are also Jewish.[54]

The bagel is a major plot device in the 2022 science-fiction film _[Everything
Everywhere All at Once](/wiki/Everything_Everywhere_All_at_Once "Everything
Everywhere All at Once")_.[55]
